title: Ask HN: Source code (Java) parser and/or static analysis tool
text:
Hi HN, for some project of mine I need a library or set of them to do the following:

Parse a potentially large code base and count, starting from an entry point that may be a main method or just a user selected method, and count how many method calls are made at the same level. Then for each call do the same recursively.

In the end I'd like to count how many calls there are for each level. Optionally I'd also like to count loops and ifs.

I think a parser or a static analysis tool could be best for the job but given I need a very simple thing (I think) I'd like to know the faster thing to get started with that gets the job done.

Thanks in advance.

title: The Terrifying Choices Created by Wildfires
Have you heard of a horse named “Potoooooooo”? Name my startup after it?
text:
“Bertie, the horse owner, intended to call the young colt "Potato" and instructed the stable boy to write the name on a feed bin. The stable boy spelled the name as "Potoooooooo" (Pot followed by 8 "o"s; that is, a failed attempt at spelling phonetically), which so amused Bertie that he adopted the spelling. Potoooooooo (1773 – November 1800) won over 30 races and defeated some of the greatest racehorses of the time.”

I’m building a bunch of developer tools and thinking of using the name Pot8o for my startup. What do you think about this name? Love to hear your thoughts.

PS: I’ve already bought domain pot8o.io

Ask HN: Setting up Architecture Review process for large teams
text:
What are some of the best practices that you have used to help ensure different teams within your organization are well equipped with their architectural decisions.

We have one Engineering Fellow that wants to ensure that engineers in all 4 teams across the company are well equipped to get feedback on their architectural decisions.

For now we are just holding office hours but as the teams grow this is becoming a challenge.

So wondering how others are setting this up.

For reference: each team is about 10-20 engineers.
